,"is_placeholder":false,"former_ids":[],"baptism":{},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Militia ensign in King Philip's War","body":"When King Philip's War broke out in 1675, Samuel was appointed ensign in the Milford militia at roughly age 29. He served through the war and its recurring aftermath of Indian skirmishes, rising to captain of the Milford militia by 1698."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Represented Milford fifteen times in the General Court","body":"He represented Milford in fifteen sessions of the Connecticut General Court between 1691 and 1703 — a span of sustained civic service that ran alongside his captaincy of the militia. His father Roger Newton Sr. had helped found the town's church."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Thomas Hooker left him £10 in his will","body":"He was nine months old when his grandfather Rev. Thomas Hooker died in 1647. Thomas's will left a £10 legacy to him — a substantial inheritance for a Hooker grandchild born during the Hartford founding."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"His wife and cousin's wife were Fenn half-sisters","body":"His wife Martha Fenn's half-sister Susanna married William Hooker — Samuel's first cousin. The Fenn family thus connected to the Hooker tree twice in the same generation through different lines."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"A second marriage to a soldier's widow","body":"After Martha Fenn died, Samuel married Sarah Welch Fowler, widow of John Fowler, who had been killed taking an Indian fort in 1693. Their son Abner bore a name found nowhere else in the Newton or Hooker line."}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"artworks":[],"career":[{"role":"Representative","organization":"Connecticut General Court","start_year":1691,"end_year":1703,"notes":"Represented Milford in 15 sessions of the General Court, 1691-1